Year = {2025},
Month = {2025 FEB 26},
Abstract = {Future Internet-of-Things (IoT) based Wireless Body Area Networks
   (WBANs) are characterised by densely populated Body Sensor Nodes (BSNs)
   with limited battery capacity. One of the significant challenges in
   IoT-based WBANs is to develop a Medium Access Control (MAC) protocol
   that is efficient in terms of BSNs' energy consumption, ensures reliable
   communication, optimises channel bandwidth utilisation, and finds the
   best possible performance of the network. Therefore, this paper proposes
   a Multi-Phase Multi-Objective (MPMO) Grasshopper Optimisation Algorithm
   (GOA) oriented Medium Access Control (MAC) protocol, namely
   MPMO-GOA-MAC, which mainly consists of a frame structure having three
   different phases, namely the Time Slots Allocation Phase (TSAP),
   Transmission Phase (TP), and Inactive Phase (IP). During TSAP, data
   packet prioritisation takes place, which minimises the channel access
   collisions among the BSNs. During TP, a Time Division Multiple Access
   (TDMA) mechanism having variable-sized time-slots is used for data
   packet transmission to improve the channel utilisation. Lastly, during
   IP, BSNs go into sleep mode to save energy. Additionally, a GOA-based
   optimisation mechanism is used to optimise the lengths of TSAP, TP, and
   IP durations in the protocol. The simulation results show that the
   proposed protocol achieves 2.19\%, 8.89\%, and 12.86\% improvement in
   throughput and 6.96\%, 14.07\%, and 18.93\% less average data packet
   delay as compared to Multi-Class-MAC, NP-CSMA/TDMA-MAC, and BASEline-MAC
   schemes, respectively. Additionally, the proposed protocol achieves 8\%,
   29.1\%, and 540\% less energy consumption as compared to PrEE-MAC,
   Multi-Class-MAC, and BASEline-MAC protocols, respectively.},
