Organization = {IEEE Turkey Sect},
Abstract = {Wireless Body Area Network (WBAN) is gaining significant popularity due
   to its applications in smart health. It facilitates efficient,
   cost-effective, ubiquitous, and unobtrusive remote e-health monitoring.
   Similar to other networks such as Wireless Sensor Network (WSN) and
   Ad-hoc Network, WBAN challenges include Postural Body Movement,
   Temperature Rise and Interference, Network Lifetime, and QoS. However,
   due to its stricter resource constrains in terms of transmit power and
   environmental requirement especially for nodes implanted in the body, an
   energy and Quality of Service aware routing protocol was developed in
   this paper. The algorithm decreases the frequent recharging and
   replacing of sensors nodes. The routing protocol works as follows:
   first, the sensor node senses the data and the data is classified into
   emergency, low-emergency and normal data by a Modified-MAC protocol
   referred to as M-MAC. Next, the emergency data is transmitted using
   single-hop transmission in order to deliver the data in on time, normal
   data is not transmitted so as to save energy and the low-emergency data
   is transmitted using another new developed algorithm called Weight-based
   optimal energy and QoS algorithm (W-QoS) which select the optimal route
   to send the data to the sink node. By enabling W-QoS to transmit
   low-emergency data, network lifetime and QoS is improved. This work is
   validated by comparing the network lifetime, delay and through to that
   of similar works, and our work outperforms all similar works. The
   performance was evaluated using OMNeT++ simulation environment.},
