Abstract = {Body area networks is an emerging field in the healthcare industry. The
   BAN for medical applications cover continuous waveform sampling of
   biomedical signals, monitoring of vital signal information, and low rate
   remote control of medical devices. In order to fulfill the diverse
   medical applications, these networks have to follow stringent technical
   requirements in terms of reliability (QoS), low power, data rate and
   noninterference. To meet these requirements, researchers have set up a
   task group 802.15.6 which is particularly working for BAN. Out of the
   available communication standards, IEEE 802.15.4 seems to be the nearest
   suitable candidate for MBAN. However the researchers have pointed out
   unsuitability of available 802.15.4 standard in terms of scalability and
   interference issues. This paper suggests modification in the MAC
   superframe structure of existing 802.15.4 and thereby addresses the
   scalability issue. The modified protocol is simulated for performance
   metrics such as throughput, power consumption, and delay. There is
   appreciable improvement in performance metrics with modified protocol
